Observer Design Pattern in C# (A to Z) – Easiest Explanation
The Observer Pattern is one of the most commonly used design patterns in real-world applications.

1. Why Observer Pattern Came Into Picture?
Imagine you have a Property Selling Application.

When a new property is listed:

Email notification should be sent.
SMS notification should be sent.
Mobile app notification should be sent.
Admin should be notified.
Without Observer Pattern:

public class PropertyService
{
    public void AddProperty()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Property Added");

        SendEmail();
        SendSms();
        SendPushNotification();
        NotifyAdmin();
    }
}
Problem
Tomorrow business says:

Add WhatsApp notification.
Add Telegram notification.
You must keep modifying the same class.

The class becomes huge.

This violates:

Open/Closed Principle
Single Responsibility Principle
2. What is Observer Pattern?
Easy Definition
Observer Pattern is used when one object changes and multiple other objects should automatically get notified.

Think:

One Publisher
      ↓
Many Subscribers
      ↓
Automatic Notification
Real-Life Example
YouTube Channel

You subscribe to a channel.

When a new video is uploaded:

YouTube Channel
      ↓
Subscriber 1
Subscriber 2
Subscriber 3
Subscriber 4
Everyone gets notified automatically.

This is Observer Pattern.

3. Observer Pattern Terminology
There are two main actors.

Subject (Publisher)
Produces updates.

Example:

YouTube Channel
Stock Market
Weather Station
Property Service
Observer (Subscriber)
Receives updates.

Example:

Email Service
SMS Service
Push Notification Service
Admin Service
Diagram
                Subject
                    |
        -----------------------
        |          |          |
    Email      SMS       Mobile App
   Observer   Observer    Observer
4. Structure of Observer Pattern
Subject
Maintains subscriber list.

Observer
Receives notifications.

Concrete Observers
Actual subscribers.

Concrete Subject
Actual publisher.

5. Step-by-Step Coding
Step 1: Create Observer Interface
public interface IObserver
{
    void Update(string message);
}
Every observer must implement Update().

Step 2: Email Observer
public class EmailObserver : IObserver
{
    public void Update(string message)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Email Sent: {message}");
    }
}
Step 3: SMS Observer
public class SmsObserver : IObserver
{
    public void Update(string message)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"SMS Sent: {message}");
    }
}
Step 4: Push Notification Observer
public class PushNotificationObserver : IObserver
{
    public void Update(string message)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Push Notification: {message}");
    }
}
Step 5: Create Subject Interface
public interface ISubject
{
    void Attach(IObserver observer);

    void Detach(IObserver observer);

    void Notify(string message);
}
Step 6: Concrete Subject
public class PropertyService : ISubject
{
    private readonly List<IObserver> _observers =
        new List<IObserver>();

    public void Attach(IObserver observer)
    {
        _observers.Add(observer);
    }

    public void Detach(IObserver observer)
    {
        _observers.Remove(observer);
    }

    public void Notify(string message)
    {
        foreach (var observer in _observers)
        {
            observer.Update(message);
        }
    }

    public void AddProperty(string propertyName)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{propertyName} Added");

        Notify($"New Property Added: {propertyName}");
    }
}
Step 7: Client Code
class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        PropertyService propertyService =
            new PropertyService();

        propertyService.Attach(
            new EmailObserver());

        propertyService.Attach(
            new SmsObserver());

        propertyService.Attach(
            new PushNotificationObserver());

        propertyService.AddProperty(
            "Luxury Villa");
    }
}
Output
Luxury Villa Added

Email Sent:
New Property Added: Luxury Villa

SMS Sent:
New Property Added: Luxury Villa

Push Notification:
New Property Added: Luxury Villa
